event.description:
July 7 - 18, 2016 from 9am to 6pm This July for twelve days only, San Francisco Botanical Garden (SFBG) once again becomes the city's own outdoor concert hall and everyone is invited to play and listen. From July 7 - 18, visitors are encouraged to seek out one of the twelve pianos tucked among the many flower-filled gardens within SFBG's 55 acres and play what they like, from Bach to boogie-woogie. On select days, professional pianists will be scheduled to perform as well, and the public is welcome to watch the performances.

Back by popular demand and now in its second year, Flower Piano is a project of piano ninjas Mauro ffortissimo and Dean Mermell who together launched Sunset Piano in 2013 when ffortissimo covertly rolled an old grand piano onto the bluffs over Half Moon Bay. Since then, Sunset Piano has expanded this impromptu musical and social experiment, temporarily placing pianos in a wide variety of unexpected natural and urban settings around the Bay Area every year, from the top of Montara Mountain to Market Street.

MORE INFO:
Website: http://www.sfbotanicalgarden.org/75/flower_piano.html
Email: blange@sfbg.org
Phone: 415-661-1316 x411 Submitted by the FullCalendar Event Promotion Service
event.title: Flower Piano

event.description: Sprouts' Afternoon Cooking Program!  Get YOUR aspiring chef at home in on the culinary craze! Afternoon Cooking for Home-school Chefs! Cook with Sprouts' Chef in our kitchen every week! Since 2011, Sprouts has offered after-school cooking programs to select schools in the Bay Area. Butthis year is the first time ever that we are opening our afternoon cooking series to home-school students in the East Bay! Each week will focus on different culinary skills and ingredients, creating delicious recipes using organic, seasonal ingredients. Spring is in the air! Students will be learning about where our food is from, when it is in season, and how to utilize the amazing local produce of the Bay Area! As we cook and eat our creations, we'll also learn, hands-on, how delicious and easy balanced and nutritional eating can be!  Enroll while there are still spots open!  6-week Series! Starting April 29th to June 3rd; Fridays, 1:00 - 2:30 p.m.  For ages 7 to 12 years old Location: Girls Inc. of Alameda County - Instruction Kitchen (2nd floor) 510 16th St., Oakland, CA 94612 Class Fees:  $168 for the 6-week series Register Here! Email our School Program Director noelle@sproutscookingclub.org for more information! ​ Sprouts is thrilled to share their love for wholesome food and hands-on cooking with your aspiring chefs! As we examine how and when our local food is grown, your aspiring chef will do everything themselves, from prep work ​and​ cooking to tasting enjoying the recipe that they created!​​What's on the menu?! All of our menus will be determined by the season’s best and inspired by local favorites! We’ll be cooking with​ Riverdog, Bluehouse, and Twin Girls Farms' produce and Straus and Organic Pastures dairy to rediscover the flavors and food culture of where we live, and gain confidence to cook for family and friends!  Sample recipes for the spring season include fresh ricotta gnocchi with pea shoots and mushrooms, corn and zucchini flat breads, lemon berry pies, and fresh juice with local citrus and watermelon!​We focus on simple, delicious and nutritious recipes that allow plenty of room forour aspiring chefs to add their own creative twist! At the end of each class, every child will enjoy the recipe that they made!​ All skill levels welcome!
event.title: Spring 2016 Home-school Afternoon Series at Sprouts!

event.description: Date: April 29-30, 2016 Time: 9am-5pm PST (both days) Location: Studio 4 in San Francisco, CA *Bonus student only VIP Day on Sunday, May 1st from 9am-5pm PST My name is Amanda Loveland, and today I am the proud and privileged Founder & CEO of Wealth University. I have built two six-figure businesses before the age of 30, all while working part-time and enjoying my life – traveling, building relationships, and spending plenty of time outdoors. But, it wasn’t always this way… In January 2013, I was a business owner with no income. I was doing all the right things and studying in all the right programs and keeping the right attitude, but my life was a f***ing mess. I would wake up at dawn and start working – writing blog posts, researching potential speaking opportunities, spending time on social media connecting with potential customers… and I would work well into the night attending networking events and pretending that I was super successful so people would want to work with me. Months into that kind of business operation, I had absolutely nothing to show for it (unless you count extreme anxiety, multiple meltdowns, and a pile of debt). I knew that I was born to help people in a BIG way, and I could feel in my bones a knowing that I could do it. But… I was defeated, confused, and headed for a major breakdown.  Do you know that feeling? The feeling of exhaustion, confusion, and defeat? Ugh. I knew I wouldn’t give up, but the issues in my life (the debt, the fear that I wouldn’t be able to pay my rent, the creeping thoughts of needing to get another job to make some money) were feeling really BIG, and my potential was starting to feel smaller and smaller. My spouse at the time was fully supporting us financially, working a job he HATED, and his patience for my “I can do this!” business strategy and my major personal development investments had officially worn out.  So, I took a major risk. I invested in myself “one more time,” and I didn’t tell my spouse about it. And, I split our finances completely. I told him, “if I cannot buy groceries, have no pity on me. If I cannot buy it, I will not have it.” I’m not promising that you’ll achieve the same exact results within the next 4 months (which, many of our students do), but I do know this… I had no money, no leads, no connections inviting me to speak at their events, no website, no real business knowledge and no prior success (I didn’t even have a program to sell at that point)… all leading to very little self confidence. But I had a deep burning desire to help people make a difference in their lives, and to become financially wealthy in the process. I can tell, you have that, too. I've helped service & product based entrepreneurs to go from a $12k lifetime revenue to passing the 6-figure mark in just 4 months time. When one of our students was asked whether or not Wealth University's content was helping her grow her business she said, "Ummmm....quadruple plussed my income. I would say it's working!" I've watched out students go from working a really "hard" 40-hour work week (with little financial benefits) to working a simple 10-hour work week and generating 218% more revenue. I've shown brand new entrepreneurs, without a clear plan and $0 revenue, get off the ground and generating consistent cash flow in less than 30 days. Here's what a past Wealth University LIVE attendee had to say (after just day one)... "It's been amazing to surround myself with women who are strong and willing to push me to be my best... if you're ever considering working with Amanda, it's worth every penny. I would have paid 2x as much for what I've learned in just the first day." I'll continue sharing these incredible success stories to propose that... You, too, can generate serious income and increase your impact at incredible levels without all the struggle. And at Wealth University LIVE, I'll show you exactly HOW I did, and exactly HOW our students do it over and over again. This is a 2-day experience in San Francisco, CA, and you'll not only be deeply immersed in the teaching and tools you need to make 2016 your most successful year ever, you'll also be surrounded by empowering, open-minded, high-achieving entrepreneurs who are in the same boat as you. They're ready to hear your story, encourage you to grow, and connect with you on a deep level. So... do you want: Clarity about what you want to create and what your business offers the world? An understanding of HOW to communicate what you're selling so people JUMP at the opportunity to buy it? A confidence that you know WHAT to spend your time doing each day to ensure you reach your goals? A clear buying process so you get a clear "yes" or clear "no," so you're not chasing people down or feel like you're pushing them to make a decision? AND a firm understanding of WHERE your ideal customers/clients are so you know what to do to sign new people EVERY single week? Join us at Wealth University LIVE, and I'll make sure you have EVERYTHING you need to get to that next level of your business. Because, 2016 is supposed to be YOUR big year, right?! I like to keep this event intimate, to ensure that I really get the time to know and connect with you.  There are only 15 seats available, and we will sell out. Reserve your seat now for this high energy event which includes spiritual AND practical tools that will give you exactly what you need to grow your business from where it is now to where you would LOVE for it to be by the end of  2016. I deeply believe that your becoming wealthy is the greatest gift you can give to the world - it's such a privilege to show people how they can increase their income and their impact, all while taking plenty of time to enjoy life. If you're feeling "on the fence" about whether or not this event is right for you, feel free to sign up for a time to talk directly with me, Amanda Loveland, to ask your questions and understand more fully whether or not this event is the place for you: SIGN UP TO ASK QUESTIONS with Amanda I'll look forward to seeing you at Wealth University LIVE on April 29 & 30 in San Francisco, CA!

event.description: The Long Now Foundation welcomes Edward Slingerland (Chinese language and religion scholar) "Creativity, Trust and the Paradox of Spontaneity" co-presented with the Center for Advanced Study in the Behavioral Sciences @ The Interval at Long Now: check-in begins at 6:30; talk will start at 7:30  Our speaker's book Trying Not to Try will be on sale and he will sign it after the talk Join us afterwards for drinks and conversation with our speaker With the paradox of wu-wei, Chinese thinkers anticipated aspects of modern neuroscience more than two millennia ago. Chinese language and religion scholar Edward Slingerland discusses wu-wei’s contemporary relevance to creativity, trust, virtue, and the future of human cooperation. Edward Slingerland is professor of Asian studies and Canada Research Chair in Chinese Thought and Embodied Cognition at the University of British Columbia, where he also holds adjunct appointments in philosophy and psychology. His book Trying Not to Try was a Guardian Best Book of 02014 and chosen by Brain Pickings as Best Book on Psychology / Philosophy for that year. "Slingerland’s book exemplifies the very principles it elucidates. Although the material is sophisticated, we effortlessly glide through a highly original integration of ancient wisdom and modern science..." —Jonathan Schooler (Prof. of Psychological and Brain Sciences, UC-Santa Barbara) During Dr. Slingerland's current residential fellowship at Stanford's CASBS he is working on a book-length project about conceptions of body and mind in early (5th-3rd c. BCE) China. This work will call into question neo-Orientalist myths about Chinese or “Eastern” thought. He is also researching the role of intoxicants and ecstatic experience in the rise of human civilization, and he is continuing to direct an international, interdisciplinary project on the evolution of religion and morality. Long Now is pleased to continue our collaboration with CASBS. This is the second of several Interval talks this year that will feature 02016 CASBS fellows. Since 01954 CASBS has been a preeminent national and international locus for cutting-edge, interdisciplinary, and transformative thinking and research on some of the most important challenges and issues. Its aim is discovery in the service of advancing social science methods, theories, and topics that address and answer socially significant questions. At the heart of the CASBS enterprise is its residential fellowship program, which attracts the finest minds from psychology, sociology, economics, political science, anthropology, history, philosophy, linguistics, and related disciplines. Edward Slingerland is professor of Asian studies and Canada Research Chair in Chinese Thought and Embodied Cognition at the University of British Columbia, where he also holds adjunct appointments in philosophy and psychology. His research specialties and teaching interests include early Chinese thought, religious studies (comparative religion, cognitive science of religion), cognitive linguistics (blending and conceptual metaphor theory), ethics (virtue ethics, moral psychology), and the relationship between the humanities and the natural sciences. He earned his B.A. with Distinction from Stanford University in Chinese (01991), his M.A. in classical Chinese from UC Berkeley (01994), and his Ph.D. in Religious Studies from Stanford (01998), where he wrote his dissertation on the topic of wu-wei and the paradox of wu-wei—the first major academic treatment of this topic. His books include Effortless Action: Wu-wei as Conceptual Metaphor and Spiritual Ideal in Early China (02003), What Science Offers the Humanities: Integrating Body & Culture (02008), and Trying Not to Try (02014), and a co-editor of Creating Consilience: Integrating the Sciences and the Humanities (02011). Join us for a talk about body & mind, science & instinct, and how historical knowledge benefits our present and future. Long Now members hear about Interval events first: become a member today
event.title: Edward Slingerland at The Interval: Creativity, Trust and the Paradox of Spontaneity

event.description: Jeremy Scahill, Investigative Reporter; Co Founder, The Intercept; Author, The Assassination Complex: Inside the Government’s Secret Drone Warfare Program; Twitter @jeremyscahill  Bestselling author Jeremy Scahill and his colleagues at the investigative website The Intercept reveal what they call stunning new details about America’s secret assassination policy. When the U.S. government discusses drone strikes publicly, the implicit message from the Obama administration has been characterized as "trust, but don’t verify." The Intercept called this into question when it obtained a cache of secret slides that provide a window into the inner workings of the U.S. military’s kill/capture operations in Afghanistan, Yemen and Somalia. These documents raise serious questions about the central role that assassination plays in counterterrorism policy. Location: 555 Post St., San Francisco  Time: 6 p.m. check-in, 6:30 p.m. program, 7:30 p.m. book signing Cost: $22 nonmembers, $12 members, $7 students (with valid ID); Premium (includes priority seating and a copy of the book): $55 nonmembers, $45 members    All ticket sales are final and nonrefundable.
event.title: Jeremy Scahill: The Government's Secret War with Drones
